[[sn:Sōgamae]]
[[ja:%E6%83%A3%E6%A7%8B]]
[[sn:ōgamae]]

<!--Sōgamae--><!--Sōgamae-->

{{otheruses|[[:en:Castle walls|Castle walls]] and their enclosures|The place name "Sōgawa" in [[Toyama City]], [[Toyama Prefecture]]|総曲輪}}
{{Special characters|description=[[Microsoft Code Page 932]] (Hagoromo High)}}
[[File:Edo hori.png|thumb|250px|right|The "Sōgamae" of Edo Castle]]
'''Sōgamae''' (総構え) refers to the '''outer enclosure''' of a [[:en:Castle|Castle]] or [[:en:Fortress|Fortress]], or the area enclosed within it. In Japan, it particularly denotes a castle structure where the outer perimeter, including the [[:en:Castle town|Castle town]] and the retainers' quarters, is surrounded by [[moats]], [[stone walls]], and [[earthen embankments]]. It is also called '''Sōkō''' (惣構), '''Sōguruwa''' (総曲輪), or '''Sōguruwa''' (総郭).

== Overview ==
In Japan, factors such as limited incursions by foreign forces and the country's mountainous terrain meant that walled cities, common on the continent, did not develop extensively, with some exceptions. Instead, fortifications such as [[palisades]] and "yakata" (fortified residences of warriors protected by moats and towers) evolved during the [[Medieval Japan|medieval period]] into [[mountain castles]].

By the early modern period, castles became not only military outposts but also political and administrative centers. To defend the castle town and the residences of retainers, an additional outer line of defense was built beyond the inner defensive structures (inner enclosure). This outer defense is what is referred to as "Sōgamae." Typically, "castle" refers only to the inner enclosure, while the "Sōgamae" often included natural terrain such as mountains and rivers, making its boundaries ambiguous. The moat of a "Sōgamae" is called a "Sōbori" (惣堀) but is often referred to as the "outer moat." However, the term "outer moat" can sometimes refer to the moat outside the castle's main enclosure rather than the "Sōgamae" moat.

The "Sōgamae" of [[Odawara Castle]], a stronghold of the [[Late Hōjō clan]], was surrounded by trenches and embankments that stretched for 2.5 leagues (approximately 9 km), enclosing the entire castle town. {{refnest|group=Note|According to [[Tsunao Nishimata]], the layout of Odawara Castle’s Sōgamae was not primarily for enclosing the settlement but was rationally designed for defense. For example, the [[Itabashi]] post station (a medieval [[Tokaido]] inn) was excluded from the Sōgamae line, while the eastern boundary extended to the [[Sannogawa]] river, despite the plains between the river and the castle center not being densely populated.<ref>[[#Nishimata2003|Nishimata 2003]], pp. 27–29.</ref>}}

The outer enclosure of [[Osaka Castle]] also extended for 2 leagues. During the [[Siege of Osaka#Winter Campaign|Winter Campaign of the Siege of Osaka]], an outwork called [[Sanadamaru]] was constructed outside the southern gate of the outer enclosure, preventing the [[Tokugawa clan|Tokugawa forces]] from breaching the enclosure. The outer enclosure of [[:en:Edo Castle|Edo Castle]] during the [[:en:Edo period|Edo period]] was the largest, with its moats, stone walls, and fences forming a spiral pattern that encompassed the entire city of Edo.

A typical example of a "Sōgamae" can be found in the [[Chinese castles]] and medieval European cities, which were surrounded by moats and ramparts (castle walls). The medieval city of [[Sakai]] was enclosed on three sides by moats 3 meters deep and 10 meters wide, with gates for defense. The [[Odoi]] in [[:en:Kyoto|Kyoto]], a typical "Sōgamae," had a total length of 5 leagues and 26 town blocks (22.4 km). {{refnest|group=Note|The "Odoi" included embankments and moats, each approximately 20 meters wide.<ref>[[#Nakamura2003|Nakamura 2003]], p. 316.</ref>}}
<gallery>
File:OdoiOmiya.jpg|The Odoi moat in [[:en:Kita-ku, Kyoto|Kita-ku, Kyoto]]
File:Himeji-castletown-plan.jpg|The "Sōgamae" of [[Himeji Castle]] and the town layout along the main roads (Culture Year 3, 1806)
File:Kooriyamajyou soukuruwa.jpg|The "Sōgamae" of [[:en:Koriyama Castle|Koriyama Castle]]<br />{{National Aerial Photography}}
File:福岡城曲輪分界図.png|A diagram of the sections of [[:en:Fukuoka Castle|Fukuoka Castle]]
</gallery>

== Oldest Remains ==
[[File:有岡城の総構石垣遺構の一部.jpg|thumb|Part of the "Sōgamae" stone wall remains of [[:en:Arioka Castle|Arioka Castle]]]]

The oldest known "Sōgamae" remains are those of [[:en:Arioka Castle|Arioka Castle]] (Itami Castle) in [[:en:Itami, Hyōgo|Itami, Hyōgo]], designated as a National Historic Site in 1979.<ref>‘Illustrated Medieval Castle Dictionary, Volume 3,’ p.36</ref> Originally built by the [[Itami clan]] during the [[Nanboku-chō period]], it was later renovated into a "Sōgamae" by [[:en:Araki Murashige|Araki Murashige]] during the [[Tenshō era]], and renamed "Arioka Castle." However, the castle was abandoned after just a decade.

Additionally, the [[Yamashina Honganji]], built starting in 1483, featured a grand "Sōgamae" that surrounded its temple town with massive embankments and moats. {{refnest|group=Note|The Yamashina Honganji had three concentric outer enclosures, forming a centripetal structure around the Honganji temple.<ref>[[#Fukushima2003|Fukushima 2003]], p. 327.</ref>}}
<gallery>
File:Itamij4.jpg|A drawing of Itami during the Bunroku era
File:伊丹郷町の範囲.png|Modern map of Itami City showing the extent of the "Sōgamae"
</gallery>
{{-}}

