[[ja:%E6%83%A3%E6%A7%8B]]
[[sn:ōgamae]]

<!--Sōgamae--><!--Sōgamae-->

{{otheruses|[[:en:Castle walls|Castle walls]] and their enclosures|The place name "Sōgawa" in [[Toyama City]], [[Toyama Prefecture]]|総曲輪}}
{{Special characters|description=[[Microsoft Code Page 932]] (Hagoromo High)}}
[[File:Edo hori.png|thumb|250px|right|The "Sōgamae" of Edo Castle]]
'''Sōgamae''' (総構え) refers to the '''outer enclosure''' of a [[:en:Castle|Castle]] or [[:en:Fortress|Fortress]], or the area enclosed within it. In Japan, it particularly denotes a castle structure where the outer perimeter, including the [[:en:Castle town|Castle town]] and the retainers' quarters, is surrounded by [[:en:Moats|Moats]], [[stone walls]], and [[earthen embankments]]. It is also called '''Sōkō''' (惣構), '''Sōguruwa''' (総曲輪), or '''Sōguruwa''' (総郭).

== Overview ==
In Japan, factors such as limited incursions by foreign forces and the country's mountainous terrain meant that walled cities, common on the continent, did not develop extensively, with some exceptions. Instead, fortifications such as [[palisades]] and "yakata" (fortified residences of warriors protected by moats and towers) evolved during the [[:en:Medieval Japan|medieval period]] into [[mountain castles]].

By the early modern period, castles became not only military outposts but also political and administrative centers. To defend the castle town and the residences of retainers, an additional outer line of defense was built beyond the inner defensive structures (inner enclosure). This outer defense is what is referred to as "Sōgamae." Typically, "castle" refers only to the inner enclosure, while the "Sōgamae" often included natural terrain such as mountains and rivers, making its boundaries ambiguous. The moat of a "Sōgamae" is called a "Sōbori" (惣堀) but is often referred to as the "outer moat." However, the term "outer moat" can sometimes refer to the moat outside the castle's main enclosure rather than the "Sōgamae" moat.

The "Sōgamae" of [[:en:Odawara Castle|Odawara Castle]], a stronghold of the [[:en:Later Hōjō clan|Later Hōjō clan]], was surrounded by trenches and embankments that stretched for 2.5 leagues (approximately 9 km), enclosing the entire castle town. {{refnest|group=Note|According to [[Tsunao Nishimata]], the layout of Odawara Castle’s Sōgamae was not primarily for enclosing the settlement but was rationally designed for defense. For example, the [[Itabashi]] post station (a medieval [[Tokaido]] inn) was excluded from the Sōgamae line, while the eastern boundary extended to the [[Sannogawa]] river, despite the plains between the river and the castle center not being densely populated.<ref>[[#Nishimata2003|Nishimata 2003]], pp. 27–29.</ref>}}

The outer enclosure of [[Osaka Castle]] also extended for 2 leagues. During the [[Siege of Osaka#Winter Campaign|Winter Campaign of the Siege of Osaka]], an outwork called [[Sanadamaru]] was constructed outside the southern gate of the outer enclosure, preventing the [[Tokugawa clan|Tokugawa forces]] from breaching the enclosure. The outer enclosure of [[:en:Edo Castle|Edo Castle]] during the [[:en:Edo period|Edo period]] was the largest, with its moats, stone walls, and fences forming a spiral pattern that encompassed the entire city of Edo.

A typical example of a "Sōgamae" can be found in the [[Chinese castles]] and medieval European cities, which were surrounded by moats and ramparts (castle walls). The medieval city of [[Sakai]] was enclosed on three sides by moats 3 meters deep and 10 meters wide, with gates for defense. The [[:en:Odoi|Odoi]] in [[:en:Kyoto|Kyoto]], a typical "Sōgamae," had a total length of 5 leagues and 26 town blocks (22.4 km). {{refnest|group=Note|The "Odoi" included embankments and moats, each approximately 20 meters wide.<ref>[[#Nakamura2003|Nakamura 2003]], p. 316.</ref>}}
